  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a real-life issue I've seen up close as an electrician working alongside engineers and technicians in Kansas City. It's when people, especially women and people of color, feel the pressure of negative stereotypes about their ability in science, technology, engineering, and math fields. For instance, a female apprentice might hesitate to ask questions during a workshop because she worries she'll be labeled 'not smart enough' for her gender. This isn't just about confidence; it's about systemic barriers that make people feel unwelcome in spaces where they're told they don't belong. I've seen this play out in my own community—my kids, who are curious about science, sometimes get discouraged when they see peers who don't share their interests, leading to a cycle of disengagement. Addressing stereotype threat isn't about fixing individual minds but creating environments where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of judgment. It means teachers and mentors who actively challenge stereotypes, like my own dad (who had only primary school) and I, who learned through hands-on work, can show kids that success in STEM isn't about innate talent but about practice and persistence. I believe we should address it by making STEM education more inclusive, starting with simple things like mentorship programs that connect students with diverse role models, and ensuring classrooms are welcoming spaces where everyone's voice matters. It's a long road, but it's worth it—because when kids feel they belong, they thrive.",
